    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2245749621" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2245749621" />
    <a title="Prakash Waka" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32951705-prakash-waka"><img alt="Prakash Waka" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1514765678p2/32951705.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2245749621?book_show_action=true">Jun 03, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Prakash Waka" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Prakash Waka" href="/user/show/32951705-prakash-waka">Prakash Waka</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32951705-prakash-waka?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32951705-prakash-waka?shelf=read-in-english">read-in-english</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32951705-prakash-waka?shelf=japan">japan</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2245749621" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5910761969270477940">The Sound of the Mountain, written by the 1968 literature Nobel Prize winner Kawabata Yasunari, is the story of Shingo, a businessman close to retirement with memory and family issues.<br/>This book suffers from several major problems which is a disappointment given how much this book is loved.<br/><br/>The first and biggest problem of the book is the inhumanity of the characters. They don&apos;t act like normal human beings, the conversations are completely unnatural and their character has no depth. Their entire </span>
  <span id="freeText5910761969270477940" style="display:none">The Sound of the Mountain, written by the 1968 literature Nobel Prize winner Kawabata Yasunari, is the story of Shingo, a businessman close to retirement with memory and family issues.<br />This book suffers from several major problems which is a disappointment given how much this book is loved.<br /><br />The first and biggest problem of the book is the inhumanity of the characters. They don't act like normal human beings, the conversations are completely unnatural and their character has no depth. Their entire character can be summarized in a few words which is particularly troublesome in a book focused on human relationships.<br /><br />Speaking of conversations, they are difficult to follow because of the difference between Japanese and English. Kawabata's discussions are made up of short sentences that follow one another without any indication of who is speaking and who is doing what. When there are only two characters, it's okay, but when there are three or more, it becomes very difficult to know which one is talking. I imagine that in Japanese, because of the pronoun system it is possible to know which character speaks by looking at which pronouns are used but this is a subtlety that is lost in the translation.<br /><br />The different chapters are very rambling, which, coupled with Shingo's already rambling narration and attempts at symbolism with stories of locusts or lotuses, makes the sequence of the book rather strange.<br />I also have the feeling that the author forgot certain character traits in the middle of the novel only to remember them at the end, which adds to the feeling of a lack of connection between the parts of the book. <br /><br />If the theme of death is certainly present in the book, I found the representation of the trauma of war depicted in a rather superficial way and, in general, there is a certain lack of deepening of many reflections, in particular the role of Shingo and the education given to children in their adult life problems.<br /><br />Finally, the title is strange since the sound of the mountain is not at all important in the story and only appears at the beginning of the book.<br /><br />A disappointing book that could have been much better.<br /><br />Funny note : I had to make a memo with the names of the different women in the book because of their very similar first names for a non-Japanese. Yasuko, Fusako, Kikuko, Satoko, Eiko, Kinu(ko), Kuniko or Natsuko, that's a lot of -ko.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5910761969270477940" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

