<div id="review_359105801" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/359105801" />
    <a title="Smiley " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2580971-smiley"><img alt="Smiley " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1525349534p2/2580971.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/359105801?book_show_action=true">Jul 01, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Smiley " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Smiley " href="/user/show/2580971-smiley">Smiley </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141192628" href="/book/show/9247754-the-sound-of-the-mountain">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2580971-smiley?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2580971-smiley?shelf=japan">japan</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer359105801" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10542194370243626791">3.75 stars<br/><br/>Reading this novel by Yasunari Kawabata, I think, is within its reader&apos;s capability since there are 16 chapters, each having its title from Chapter 1 The Sound of the Mountain, Chapter 2 The Wings of the Locust, Chapter 3 A Blaze of Clouds, to Chapter 16 Fish in Autumn. Moreover, in each chapter, its content&apos;s divided into mini-chapters denoted by numbers, that is, No. 1-5 for Chapter 1, No. 1-4 for Chapter 2, No. 1-3 for Chapter 3, ..., No. 1-5 in Chapter 16. In effect, this kind of v</span>
  <span id="freeText10542194370243626791" style="display:none">3.75 stars<br /><br />Reading this novel by Yasunari Kawabata, I think, is within its reader's capability since there are 16 chapters, each having its title from Chapter 1 The Sound of the Mountain, Chapter 2 The Wings of the Locust, Chapter 3 A Blaze of Clouds, to Chapter 16 Fish in Autumn. Moreover, in each chapter, its content's divided into mini-chapters denoted by numbers, that is, No. 1-5 for Chapter 1, No. 1-4 for Chapter 2, No. 1-3 for Chapter 3, ..., No. 1-5 in Chapter 16. In effect, this kind of varied sections allows its readers more space and we can enjoy reading each within our scope of concentration, thus we seldom get bored as compared to other typical novels with lengthy endless narration that seem not to care whether such a style would entice their readers or not.<br /><br />I liked this novel depicting Otaga Shingo's life as a 62-year-old man who had lived sometime since the end of World War II in a house with his wife Yasuko (63), his son named Shuichi, his daughter-in-law named Kikugo, his divorced daughter named Fusako who had returned home with two children Satoko aged four and Kuniko one (their father Aihara left them). Shingo and Shuichi worked in the same firm. Its key theme focuses on their familial relations in which there are eventual problems due to some nagging remarks, his son having a mistress named Kinu who stayed far away and Shingo's failing health. <br /><br />One day Shingo has been revealed an unthinkable incident regarding Kikugo's abortion due to, strangely, her husband's wish without having informing his father and mother. In other words, Kikugo or Shuichi should have told Shingo or Yasugo on the abortion, maybe they do not know how. This is one of those conflicts we can read along this 209-page paperback. I think Kawabata is one the great Japanese novelists whose style of writing is unique due to lots of short paragraphs, engaging lively dialogs, apt sense of humor, etc. and therefore we cannot help admiring his writing style rightly deserved his highest literary honor as the Nobel Prize recipient for literature in 1968. While reading his novels, I sometime thought it reminded me of reading Ernest Hemingway's novels and I wonder if each one had ever read the other's novels.<br /><br />Shingo's problems have increasingly escalated due to his absent-mindedness, elusive memory as well as his off and on pseudo-amorous wish toward his daughter-in-law Kikugo who dutifully keeps helping him in getting dressed, in meal serving, etc. and honoring him by respectfully calling him, 'Father,' every time she needs to address herself, therefore, he has reflected and controled himself as follows:<br /><br />A bolt flashed across his mind.<br />...<br />And might it not be that, if his desires were given free rein, if he could remake his life as he wished, he would want to love the virgin Kikugo, before she was married to Shuichi?<br />Suppressed and twisted, the subconscious wish had taken an unlovable form in his dream. Even in the dream, had he sought to hide it, to deceive himself?<br />...<br />(p. 156)<br /><br />The following sentences have mystified me:<br />1. The year before, the year he had entered his second cycle of sixty years. ... (p. 3) [Query: Does this mean Shingo was entering the second Japanese-style cycle hoping to live till 120 years old, as the second cycle?]<br /><br />2. On the desk were a pocket watch and a wrist watch. The wrist watch was two minutes the faster. (p. 79) [Query: Why the faster? Grammatically, this should be: ... two minutes faster.]<br />etc.<br /><br />Surprisingly, I found this as a good quip I have never read anywhere before. [My note: One has to see the light!]<br /><br />... 'An old man looks better when he's out with a young girl. ...' (p. 201)<br /><br />And this scene is simply similar to anywhere in Thailand in the past and now:<br /><br />Shingo found mosquito nets heavy and oppressive. He was no longer using one.<br />Yasuko complained of the deprivation every night and would make a great ceremony of swatting mosquitoes. <br />... (p. 184)<br /><br />In brief, this seemingly complex novel is worth spending our time in reading, pondering and criticizing Japanese culture in that how polite and subtle it is. It is one of those few I would like to reread when I can find free time and I would definitely find a copy of his "Beauty and Sadness" to read soon. (And I finished my second reading on December 18, 2017.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="10542194370243626791" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


