<div id="review_3394239563" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3394239563" />
    <a title="Elena Sala" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/58119141-elena-sala"><img alt="Elena Sala" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1469638554p2/58119141.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3394239563?book_show_action=true">Aug 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elena Sala" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elena Sala" href="/user/show/58119141-elena-sala">Elena Sala</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19247459-the-sound-of-the-mountain">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/58119141-elena-sala?shelf=asia">asia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/58119141-elena-sala?shelf=japan">japan</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3394239563" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1303924537237743908">Shingo is the 63 year old hero of Kawabata&apos;s THE SOUND OF THE MOUNTAIN (1953). Shingo&apos;s family is upper middle class, he lives in a beautiful sprawling traditional style house, surrounded by a carefully maintained garden, with his wife Yasuko, his son Suichi and Kikuko, his daughter in law. Shingo is an aesthete, and like Kikuko, sensitive to nature, sights, sounds and smells. <br/><br/>Shingo is aging. He admits his memory is fading these days and witnesses definitive signs of aging in himself besides th</span>
  <span id="freeText1303924537237743908" style="display:none">Shingo is the 63 year old hero of Kawabata's THE SOUND OF THE MOUNTAIN (1953). Shingo's family is upper middle class, he lives in a beautiful sprawling traditional style house, surrounded by a carefully maintained garden, with his wife Yasuko, his son Suichi and Kikuko, his daughter in law. Shingo is an aesthete, and like Kikuko, sensitive to nature, sights, sounds and smells. <br /><br />Shingo is aging. He admits his memory is fading these days and witnesses definitive signs of aging in himself besides those in nature and the people around him. He is aware that his life has not been fulfilled, that he is a floating leaf on the river of time.<br /><br />There is a quiet sense of failure at home. Suichi's and Kikuko's marriage is failing. Suichi is a womanizer, very fond of alcohol. Kikuko is sweet, shy, almost childlike. Shingo's relationship with his daughter in law is one of deep affection and sympathy, and the more Suichi screws up his marriage, the closer Shingo and Kikuko become. Kikuko calls Shingo "Father " and of course, theirs is a doomed relationship, a relationship which flirts precariously with incest, and yet the great tenderness and affection between these two characters is so moving.<br /><br />Then, Fusako, who has been abandoned by her husband, returns to her parents house with her little daughter and baby. Their presences in Shingo's house are a constant reminder of his failures as a parent. He realizes, though, that his affection for Kikuko is a blind against the failed marriages of his children and a foil for his own mortality.<br /><br />Shingo is the guardian of traditional cultural forms and his attraction to Kikuko is inseparable from her aura of refinement and traditional femininity. At one point, Shingo recognizes that he is imposing, without meaning to, a form of character onto Kikuko that is somewhat idealistic and irresponsible. He must let her go, grow up, in spite of the unbearable loss. The price of freedom, for Kikuko is deprivation: of her beloved, gentle, father in law, and the aesthetics of nature, simplicity and the old world with which he is identified. The road to female emancipation is paved with pain and uncertainty. <br /><br />THE SOUND OF THE MOUNTAIN is a novel about Shingo's mortality and Kikuko's freedom. Kawabata's prose is infused by a subtle eroticism and subtlety. I've barely outlined part of the plot and feel I had to omit many details in order to avoid spoilers. In his own meditative, quiet way, Kawabata has written a powerful novel with a plot of dramatic intensity. Mikio Naruse, the renowned Japanese director, filmed a beautiful adaptation of this novel (1954), and apparently, it is one of his personal favorite films (and he directed many, many films). I recommend both the book and the film, if you manage to find it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1303924537237743908" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


