<div id="review_3640885024" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3640885024" />
    <a title="Prateek Pradhan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/119365244-prateek-pradhan"><img alt="Prateek Pradhan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1597518931p2/119365244.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3640885024?book_show_action=true">Nov 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Prateek Pradhan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Prateek Pradhan" href="/user/show/119365244-prateek-pradhan">Prateek Pradhan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3640885024" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17537139016797927162">Picked up this classic Japanese novel to read during the festive weekend.<br/><br/>There are very few novels that have rendered the predicament of old age. And one of them is &apos;The Sound of the Mountain&apos;.<br/>The 1968 Nobel Laureate Yasunari Kawabata beautifully penned down the story of an elderly Tokyo businessman who is trapped between his failing memories and his falling apart family. <br/><br/>Only Kawabata can dissect human emotions in way which touches the reader so deeply he experiences all the pain and joys of su</span>
  <span id="freeText17537139016797927162" style="display:none">Picked up this classic Japanese novel to read during the festive weekend.<br /><br />There are very few novels that have rendered the predicament of old age. And one of them is 'The Sound of the Mountain'.<br />The 1968 Nobel Laureate Yasunari Kawabata beautifully penned down the story of an elderly Tokyo businessman who is trapped between his failing memories and his falling apart family. <br /><br />Only Kawabata can dissect human emotions in way which touches the reader so deeply he experiences all the pain and joys of such ordinary characters. This is the epitome of subtlety. The book is just about conversations, problems, relationships and daily life of ordinary people. <br />And it's only after one has finished the novel that one truly grasps the crisis; of identity and existence and it is in that moment that Kawabata-san provides a wonderful path to redemption.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17537139016797927162" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
